[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":554},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F15\u002Fre-learning-js-30-new-and-function-constructors\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F15\u002Fre-learning-js-30-new-and-function-constructors\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F15\u002Fre-learning-js-30-new-and-function-constructors\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F15\u002Fre-learning-js-30-new-and-function-constructors\u002F":529,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F15\u002Fre-learning-js-30-new-and-function-constructors\u002F":538},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20191015\u002F3030913854\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":512,"date":513,"description":514,"extension":515,"lang":516,"meta":517,"navigation":245,"path":518,"readingMinutes":519,"seo":520,"standalone":521,"stem":522,"tags":523,"tldr":526,"updated":513,"url":527,"__hash__":528},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fre-learning-js-30-new-and-function-constructors.md","RE: Learning JS From Zero, Day 30 — What new and Function Constructors Actually Do","1002209404",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":507},"minimark",[11,16,25,27,44,51,57,108,115,120,140,149,155,161,179,189,253,266,272,278,334,344,349,355,398,410,480,483,489,496,500,503],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19,20,24],"p",{},"Day 30, the last real day of this reincarnation. To close things out, let me cover one small thing we've been using all along without really explaining it: the ",[21,22,23],"code",{},"new"," keyword and function constructors.",[12,26,23],{"id":23},[17,28,29,30,33,34,33,37,40,41,43],{},"By now you've seen a ton of ",[21,31,32],{},"new Date()",", ",[21,35,36],{},"new Array()",[21,38,39],{},"new Object()"," and so on. But what actually is ",[21,42,23],{},"? It's an operator.",[17,45,46],{},[47,48],"img",{"alt":49,"src":50},"operators","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FCcN6Gkr.png",[17,52,53,54,56],{},"The thing is, whatever you build with ",[21,55,23],{}," almost always comes out as an object type. For example:",[58,59,64],"pre",{"className":60,"code":61,"language":62,"meta":63,"style":63},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","var a = new String('1234');\ntypeof(a);\n","js","",[21,65,66,99],{"__ignoreMap":63},[67,68,71,75,79,82,85,89,92,96],"span",{"class":69,"line":70},"line",1,[67,72,74],{"class":73},"sWyjQ","var",[67,76,78],{"class":77},"sMAXC"," a ",[67,80,81],{"class":73},"=",[67,83,84],{"class":73}," new",[67,86,88],{"class":87},"sj_SG"," String",[67,90,91],{"class":77},"(",[67,93,95],{"class":94},"sTRMh","'1234'",[67,97,98],{"class":77},");\n",[67,100,102,105],{"class":69,"line":101},2,[67,103,104],{"class":73},"typeof",[67,106,107],{"class":77},"(a);\n",[17,109,110,111,114],{},"The type you get back is ",[21,112,113],{},"object",".",[17,116,117],{},[47,118],{"alt":113,"src":119},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002Ff9NFuWD.png",[17,121,122,123,126,127,129,130,132,133,135,136,139],{},"You'd expect a ",[21,124,125],{},"String"," variable, but it shows up as ",[21,128,113],{},". Why? Because whatever you create with ",[21,131,23],{}," is basically a kind of object. So when you use the ",[21,134,23],{}," keyword, you're really getting ready to build an object — an empty object ",[21,137,138],{},"{}"," to start with.",[17,141,142,143,145,146,148],{},"So why does ",[21,144,23],{}," even exist? This goes back a little to JavaScript's origins. Back then JAVA was the hot language, and JavaScript's creator wanted to attract JAVA developers, so this got bolted on. The catch is that using ",[21,147,23],{}," to build things sometimes leads to slightly weird situations — like the example above.",[17,150,151,152,154],{},"The usual way you write ",[21,153,23],{}," looks like this:",[17,156,157],{},[47,158],{"alt":159,"src":160},"function constructor","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FStsn1Sw.png",[17,162,163,164,167,168,172,173,175,176,178],{},"If you've ever written Vue, you've seen ",[21,165,166],{},"new Vue"," — and that's called a ",[169,170,171],"strong",{},"Vue instance",". But how do you actually wrap your head around how ",[21,174,23],{}," works? Picture it like this: imagine in some other world there's a thing called a goblin (Vue), but it has no life — it doesn't move, doesn't attack, doesn't talk. If you want to give it life, you have to use ",[21,177,23],{},". That's what an instance is.",[17,180,181,182,184,185,188],{},"One thing to watch out for though: ",[21,183,23],{}," also changes what ",[21,186,187],{},"this"," points to. Let's start with a basic example:",[58,190,192],{"className":60,"code":191,"language":62,"meta":63,"style":63},"function fu() {\n  console.log(this);\n}\nvar a = fu();\n\na;\n",[21,193,194,205,220,226,240,247],{"__ignoreMap":63},[67,195,196,199,202],{"class":69,"line":70},[67,197,198],{"class":73},"function",[67,200,201],{"class":87}," fu",[67,203,204],{"class":77},"() {\n",[67,206,207,210,213,215,218],{"class":69,"line":101},[67,208,209],{"class":77},"  console.",[67,211,212],{"class":87},"log",[67,214,91],{"class":77},[67,216,187],{"class":217},"sCcAr",[67,219,98],{"class":77},[67,221,223],{"class":69,"line":222},3,[67,224,225],{"class":77},"}\n",[67,227,229,231,233,235,237],{"class":69,"line":228},4,[67,230,74],{"class":73},[67,232,78],{"class":77},[67,234,81],{"class":73},[67,236,201],{"class":87},[67,238,239],{"class":77},"();\n",[67,241,243],{"class":69,"line":242},5,[67,244,246],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":245},true,"\n",[67,248,250],{"class":69,"line":249},6,[67,251,252],{"class":77},"a;\n",[17,254,255,256,258,259,262,263,114],{},"Here you can see ",[21,257,187],{}," currently points to ",[21,260,261],{},"window",", which lines up perfectly with what we covered back on Day 19 — ",[169,264,265],{},"this is decided by how you call the function",[17,267,268],{},[47,269],{"alt":270,"src":271},"Window","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FyudeNVR.png",[17,273,274,275,277],{},"But what happens when you throw ",[21,276,23],{}," into the mix?",[58,279,281],{"className":60,"code":280,"language":62,"meta":63,"style":63},"function fu() {\n  console.log(this);\n}\n\nvar a = new fu();\n\na;\n",[21,282,283,291,303,307,311,325,329],{"__ignoreMap":63},[67,284,285,287,289],{"class":69,"line":70},[67,286,198],{"class":73},[67,288,201],{"class":87},[67,290,204],{"class":77},[67,292,293,295,297,299,301],{"class":69,"line":101},[67,294,209],{"class":77},[67,296,212],{"class":87},[67,298,91],{"class":77},[67,300,187],{"class":217},[67,302,98],{"class":77},[67,304,305],{"class":69,"line":222},[67,306,225],{"class":77},[67,308,309],{"class":69,"line":228},[67,310,246],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":245},[67,312,313,315,317,319,321,323],{"class":69,"line":242},[67,314,74],{"class":73},[67,316,78],{"class":77},[67,318,81],{"class":73},[67,320,84],{"class":73},[67,322,201],{"class":87},[67,324,239],{"class":77},[67,326,327],{"class":69,"line":249},[67,328,246],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":245},[67,330,332],{"class":69,"line":331},7,[67,333,252],{"class":77},[17,335,336,337,339,340,343],{},"And there it is — something interesting happened. ",[21,338,187],{}," changed and now points to an empty object, and that empty object is ",[21,341,342],{},"fu()"," itself.",[17,345,346],{},[47,347],{"alt":113,"src":348},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FtETSpI6.png",[17,350,351,352,354],{},"We've talked about a few ways to create objects already, and ",[21,353,23],{}," is just another one of them. Let me show the original object-literal way of adding properties:",[58,356,358],{"className":60,"code":357,"language":62,"meta":63,"style":63},"var fu = {};\n\nfu.name = 'Ray';\n\nfu;\n",[21,359,360,372,376,389,393],{"__ignoreMap":63},[67,361,362,364,367,369],{"class":69,"line":70},[67,363,74],{"class":73},[67,365,366],{"class":77}," fu ",[67,368,81],{"class":73},[67,370,371],{"class":77}," {};\n",[67,373,374],{"class":69,"line":101},[67,375,246],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":245},[67,377,378,381,383,386],{"class":69,"line":222},[67,379,380],{"class":77},"fu.name ",[67,382,81],{"class":73},[67,384,385],{"class":94}," 'Ray'",[67,387,388],{"class":77},";\n",[67,390,391],{"class":69,"line":228},[67,392,246],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":245},[67,394,395],{"class":69,"line":242},[67,396,397],{"class":77},"fu;\n",[17,399,400,401,33,404,406,407,409],{},"We already know that inside ",[21,402,403],{},"var a = new fu();",[21,405,187],{}," points to an empty object — that is, ",[21,408,138],{},". So the way you write properties onto it looks like this:",[58,411,413],{"className":60,"code":412,"language":62,"meta":63,"style":63},"function fu() {\n  this.name = 'Ray';\n  console.log(this);\n}\n\nvar a = new fu();\n\na;\n",[21,414,415,423,437,449,453,457,471,475],{"__ignoreMap":63},[67,416,417,419,421],{"class":69,"line":70},[67,418,198],{"class":73},[67,420,201],{"class":87},[67,422,204],{"class":77},[67,424,425,428,431,433,435],{"class":69,"line":101},[67,426,427],{"class":217},"  this",[67,429,430],{"class":77},".name ",[67,432,81],{"class":73},[67,434,385],{"class":94},[67,436,388],{"class":77},[67,438,439,441,443,445,447],{"class":69,"line":222},[67,440,209],{"class":77},[67,442,212],{"class":87},[67,444,91],{"class":77},[67,446,187],{"class":217},[67,448,98],{"class":77},[67,450,451],{"class":69,"line":228},[67,452,225],{"class":77},[67,454,455],{"class":69,"line":242},[67,456,246],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":245},[67,458,459,461,463,465,467,469],{"class":69,"line":249},[67,460,74],{"class":73},[67,462,78],{"class":77},[67,464,81],{"class":73},[67,466,84],{"class":73},[67,468,201],{"class":87},[67,470,239],{"class":77},[67,472,473],{"class":69,"line":331},[67,474,246],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":245},[67,476,478],{"class":69,"line":477},8,[67,479,252],{"class":77},[17,481,482],{},"Both end up the same.",[17,484,485],{},[47,486],{"alt":487,"src":488},"same result","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002F0EWtli0.png",[17,490,491,492,495],{},"Building things with ",[21,493,494],{},"new function"," like that is what we call a function constructor (also known as a constructor function).",[12,497,499],{"id":498},"wrap-up","Wrap-up",[17,501,502],{},"Next up is RE: Learning JS From Zero, Day 31 — the last day of this reincarnation, a little bonus chapter. That one's just the closing thoughts.",[504,505,506],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sj_SG, html code.shiki .sj_SG{--shiki-default:#DBB7FF}html pre.shiki code .sTRMh, html code.shiki .sTRMh{--shiki-default:#ADDCFF}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html pre.shiki code .sCcAr, html code.shiki .sCcAr{--shiki-default:#91CBFF}",{"title":63,"searchDepth":101,"depth":101,"links":508},[509,510,511],{"id":14,"depth":101,"text":15},{"id":23,"depth":101,"text":23},{"id":498,"depth":101,"text":499},"JavaScript","2019-10-15 00:00:01","Day 30, the last real day of the series. A quick wrap-up on something we've been quietly using the whole time: the new keyword and function constructors. We'll look at why new always gives you an object, how it changes what this points to, and how building an object with new compares to the plain object literal approach.","md","en",{},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002Fre-learning-js-30-new-and-function-constructors","3",{"title":6,"description":514},false,"en\u002FJavaScript\u002Fre-learning-js-30-new-and-function-constructors",[512,524,525],"RE：從零開始的學習 JS 生活","第 11 屆 iT邦幫忙鐵人賽",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F15\u002Fre-learning-js-30-new-and-function-constructors\u002F","hDEuYMUY7DpXrml6JuoKNVUUPrFIdTwmF5Ua1sYWZk8",{"newer":530,"older":534},{"url":531,"title":532,"date":533},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F15\u002Fjs-from-zero-extra-closing-thoughts\u002F","RE: Learning JS Life From Zero — Bonus Chapter: Closing Thoughts","2019-10-15 00:00:05",{"url":535,"title":536,"date":537},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F14\u002Fjs-from-zero-ep29-template-string\u002F","JS From Zero, Day 29: Template Strings Will Spoil You Forever","2019-10-14 00:00:01",[539,544,549],{"url":540,"title":541,"date":542,"readingMinutes":543},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2026\u002F03\u002F10\u002Fweb-crypto-api-encryption-guide\u002F","No crypto Package, No Node.js — The Web Crypto API Does It All in the Browser","2026-03-10 09:45:08","9",{"url":545,"title":546,"date":547,"readingMinutes":548},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2025\u002F12\u002F08\u002Fjquery-why-it-declined\u002F","jQuery Was Once King — So Why Did It Fall Off?","2025-12-08 21:35:24","7",{"url":550,"title":551,"date":552,"readingMinutes":553},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2025\u002F12\u002F05\u002Fjavascript-generator-functions\u002F","What Are JavaScript Generator Functions (function*)? The Function You Can Pause and Resume","2025-12-05 13:40:31","5",1784013060351]